SIMPLE: passage
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Passage
<hw>Pas"sage</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>passage</ets>. See <er>Pass</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of passing; transit from one place to another;
movement from point to point; a going by, over, across, or through;
<as>as, the <ex>passage</ex> of a man or a carriage; the
<ex>passage</ex> of a ship or a bird; the <ex>passage</ex> of light; the
<ex>passage</ex> of fluids through the pores or channels of the
body.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What! are my doors opposed against my <qex>passage</qex>!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Transit by means of conveyance; journey, as by
water, carriage, car, or the like; travel; right, liberty, or means, of
passing; conveyance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ship in which he had taken <qex>passage</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Price paid for the liberty to pass; fare; <as>as, to
pay one's <ex>passage</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Removal from life; decease; departure; death.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Endure thy mortal <xex>passage</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When he is fit and season'd for his <qex>passage</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Way; road; path; channel or course through or by
which one passes; way of exit or entrance; way of access or transit.
Hence, a common avenue to various apartments in a building; a hall; a
corridor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And with his pointed dart⟦br⟧
Explores the nearest <qex>passage</qex> to his heart.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Persian army had advanced into the . . . <qex>passages</qex>
of Cilicia.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A continuous course, process, or progress; a
connected or continuous series; <as>as, the <ex>passage</ex> of
time</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The conduct and <qex>passage</qex> of affairs.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J.
Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>passage</qex> and whole carriage of this action.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A separate part of a course, process, or series; an
occurrence; an incident; an act or deed.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧In thy
<xex>passages</xex> of life.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The . . . almost incredible <qex>passage</qex> of their
unbelief.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A particular portion constituting a part of
something continuous; esp., a portion of a book, speech, or musical
composition; a paragraph; a clause.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How commentators each dark <qex>passage</qex> shun.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Reception; currency.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir K. Digby.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>A pass or en encounter; <as>as, a <ex>passage</ex>
at arms</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No <qex>passages</qex> of love⟦br⟧
Betwixt us twain henceforward evermore.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>A movement or an evacuation of the
bowels.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>In parliamentary proceedings: <sd>(a)</sd> The
course of a proposition (bill, resolution, etc.) through the several
stages of consideration and action; <as>as, during its <ex>passage</ex>
through Congress the bill was amended in both Houses</as>. <sd>(b)</sd>
The advancement of a bill or other proposition from one stage to another
by an affirmative vote; esp., the final affirmative action of the body
upon a proposition; hence, adoption; enactment; <as>as, the
<ex>passage</ex> of the bill to its third reading was
delayed</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>passage</xex> of the Stamp
Act.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>D. Hosack.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The final question was then put upon its <qex>passage</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Cushing.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In passage</b></col>, <cd>in passing; cursorily.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧These . . . have been studied but <xex>in passage</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Bacon.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>Middle passage</b></col>,
<col><b>Northeast passage</b></col>, <col><b>Northwest
passage</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under <er>Middle</er>,
<er>Northeast</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Of passage</b></col>,
<cd>passing from one place, region, or climate, to another; migratory;
-- said especially of birds.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Birds <xex>of
passage</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Longfellow.</au> -- <col><b>Passage
hawk</b></col>, <cd>a hawk taken on its passage or migration.</cd> --
<col><b>Passage money</b></col>, <cd>money paid for conveyance of a
passenger, -- usually for carrying passengers by water.</cd> </cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1049 --></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Vestibule; hall; corridor. See
<er>Vestibule</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Passager</ent>⟦br⟧
